1
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:04,074
Subtitles downloaded from www.OpenSubtitles.org

2
00:02:28,325 --> 00:02:30,122
Excuse me, Mr. Filby.

3
00:03:43,734 --> 00:03:46,168
I say, it's outright rude of the man!

4
00:03:46,236 --> 00:03:48,864
He's merely been detained. That's all.

5
00:03:49,005 --> 00:03:51,200
This is such a confounded waste of time!

6
00:03:51,274 --> 00:03:54,937
If he's not coming, I've any number
of more important things to do.

7
00:03:59,382 --> 00:04:01,942
Well, speak up. What is it, woman?

8
00:04:11,428 --> 00:04:15,159
Well, are we or are we not invited
for dinner?

9
00:04:16,166 --> 00:04:17,292
Apparently we are.

10
00:04:18,535 --> 00:04:19,934
How long has he been gone?

11
00:04:20,337 --> 00:04:23,033
I can't rightly say, sir. Several days.

12
00:04:23,273 --> 00:04:25,434
I've hardly seen him for some time.

13
00:04:25,909 --> 00:04:30,005
He never leaves the laboratory.
He only comes in and picks at his food.

14
00:04:30,947 --> 00:04:33,108
But he did tell me about dinner tonight...

15
00:04:33,216 --> 00:04:35,411
...and left those instructions.

16
00:04:37,754 --> 00:04:39,779
Thank you, Mrs. Watchett.

17
00:04:41,191 --> 00:04:43,557
What does it say, Filby? What's wrong?

18
00:04:43,627 --> 00:04:44,889
Nothing really.

19
00:04:45,228 --> 00:04:50,097
George merely says that if he's not here
by 8:00 then we're to begin without him.

20
00:04:51,935 --> 00:04:53,903
Walter, what time is it?

21
00:04:57,574 --> 00:04:59,769
Dinner is served, gentlemen.

22
00:04:59,976 --> 00:05:03,377
First sensible thing I've heard all evening.

23
00:05:04,347 --> 00:05:05,939
This is peculiar.

24
00:05:06,283 --> 00:05:08,615
He's usually prompt, precise, and punctual.

25
00:05:08,685 --> 00:05:11,745
He's making fools of us by inviting us
and then not showing up.

26
00:05:11,822 --> 00:05:13,449
It's not the behavior of a gentleman.

27
00:05:13,523 --> 00:05:15,388
To say nothing of the waste of time.

28
00:05:15,458 --> 00:05:17,517
Yes. To say nothing of the waste of time.

29
00:05:17,594 --> 00:05:21,894
There's one thing I like about old George,
he's got the best cellar in England.

30
00:05:21,965 --> 00:05:23,296
And Mrs. Watchett...

31
00:05:23,366 --> 00:05:25,197
...is the finest cook in the world.

32
00:05:25,669 --> 00:05:27,899
Yes, I think I'll drink to that.

33
00:05:42,786 --> 00:05:44,686
Good Lord! What's happened?

34
00:05:44,754 --> 00:05:45,743
I'm all right.

35
00:05:48,658 --> 00:05:49,784
Some food.

36
00:05:52,729 --> 00:05:53,718
A drink.

37
00:06:05,575 --> 00:06:07,167
I didn't recognize you.

38
00:06:07,477 --> 00:06:08,910
Mrs. Watchett.

39
00:06:15,919 --> 00:06:18,683
Can't you speak, man?
What happened to you?

40
00:06:18,788 --> 00:06:20,722
- Leave him alone.
- No, it's all right.

41
00:06:20,891 --> 00:06:23,382
I've got to tell it now
while I still remember it.

42
00:06:23,460 --> 00:06:25,485
Relax. Try to relax.

43
00:06:25,996 --> 00:06:27,964
You've all the time in the world.

44
00:06:31,368 --> 00:06:33,165
You're right, David.

45
00:06:34,938 --> 00:06:36,735
That's exactly what I have.

46
00:06:38,541 --> 00:06:40,600
All the time in the world.

47
00:06:42,679 --> 00:06:45,079
Ever since we were together
five days ago...

48
00:06:45,515 --> 00:06:47,449
...the last day of 1899.

49
00:06:52,055 --> 00:06:55,684
There in that box rests the result
of two years' labor.

50
00:06:58,862 --> 00:07:02,559
I wanted to finish the job
before the new century began.

51
00:07:03,433 --> 00:07:05,162
I barely made it.

52
00:07:07,170 --> 00:07:08,262
Cheers, gentlemen.

53
00:07:08,338 --> 00:07:09,862
Marvelous, old boy.

54
00:07:10,473 --> 00:07:11,735
Yes, but what is it?

55
00:07:14,444 --> 00:07:16,674
Well, it has to do with time.

56
00:07:17,948 --> 00:07:20,883
I've always maintained
what this nation needs is...

57
00:07:21,151 --> 00:07:22,846
...a reliable timepiece.

58
00:07:23,753 --> 00:07:25,152
The Navy needs one.

59
00:07:25,221 --> 00:07:28,122
The Army needs one
for the artillery, you know.

60
00:07:28,658 --> 00:07:30,751
You couldn't do better, George.

61
00:07:30,894 --> 00:07:32,759
So that's why you've been in hiding?

62
00:07:33,496 --> 00:07:35,623
Very clever of you, indeed.

63
00:07:35,899 --> 00:07:39,562
I don't think George is referring
to a new type of timepiece.

64
00:07:40,904 --> 00:07:42,201
Not really.

65
00:07:44,074 --> 00:07:47,475
When I speak of time, gentlemen,
I'm referring to the fourth dimension.

66
00:07:51,381 --> 00:07:52,473
Go on, George.

67
00:07:53,917 --> 00:07:58,149
The difficulty in explaining this dimension
is that it cannot be seen or felt.

68
00:07:58,621 --> 00:08:00,179
If you don't mind, George...

69
00:08:00,991 --> 00:08:04,449
...will you refresh me
on the first three dimensions?

70
00:08:04,627 --> 00:08:05,651
Really, Filby.

71
00:08:05,729 --> 00:08:08,425
Surely they taught you something
in school.

72
00:08:08,498 --> 00:08:10,864
Suppose you explain it, Doctor.

73
00:08:12,235 --> 00:08:13,065
Certainly.

74
00:08:17,073 --> 00:08:21,100
For example, when I move in
a straight line, forward or backward...

75
00:08:21,544 --> 00:08:23,102
...that's one dimension.

76
00:08:23,179 --> 00:08:25,477
When I move to the left or the right...

77
00:08:25,548 --> 00:08:26,640
...two dimensions.

78
00:08:26,883 --> 00:08:28,817
When I move up or down...

79
00:08:29,252 --> 00:08:31,015
...three dimensions.

80
00:08:33,023 --> 00:08:34,957
For instance, that box.

81
00:08:36,526 --> 00:08:40,394
That box has three dimensions:
Length, breadth, and height.

82
00:08:40,964 --> 00:08:42,932
Yes, but what is the fourth dimension?

83
00:08:44,300 --> 00:08:48,600
That's mere theory. No one knows
if the fourth dimension even exists.

84
00:08:48,772 --> 00:08:50,171
On the contrary, Doctor.

85
00:08:50,607 --> 00:08:54,373
The fourth dimension is as real and true
a dimension as any of the other three.

86
00:08:55,245 --> 00:08:57,770
In fact, they couldn't exist without it.

87
00:08:57,847 --> 00:08:58,973
What do you mean?

88
00:09:00,517 --> 00:09:02,178
Let's take that box.

89
00:09:02,986 --> 00:09:05,454
It has the first three dimensions,
as you said.

90
00:09:05,755 --> 00:09:08,349
- All right. What's in that box?
- I'm coming to that.

91
00:09:08,425 --> 00:09:10,222
Let's consider this first.

92
00:09:10,293 --> 00:09:13,126
Why is it that we usually ignore
the fourth dimension?

93
00:09:13,263 --> 00:09:15,561
Because we have no freedom
of movement within it.

94
00:09:15,632 --> 00:09:17,463
We can move in the other three:

95
00:09:17,534 --> 00:09:20,503
Up, down, forward, sideways, backward,
as the doctor said...

96
00:09:20,770 --> 00:09:23,739
...but when it comes to time,
we are prisoners.

97
00:09:28,244 --> 00:09:30,405
Do you follow me, Bridewell?

98
00:09:30,480 --> 00:09:31,344
No!

99
00:09:34,784 --> 00:09:36,979
You've given a most lucid explanation...

100
00:09:37,053 --> 00:09:39,544
...but I'm afraid I don't quite understand.

101
00:09:40,023 --> 00:09:43,424
There are many things in this world
you don't understand, aren't there?

102
00:09:43,493 --> 00:09:44,983
Yes, quite. Quite a number.

103
00:09:45,061 --> 00:09:47,996
You don't refuse to believe in them,
because of that, do you?

104
00:09:48,064 --> 00:09:50,999
No, not if I can see the proof
with my own eyes.

105
00:09:51,067 --> 00:09:52,398
Good, Walter.

106
00:09:53,136 --> 00:09:55,627
Gentlemen, all I'm asking you to do now...

107
00:09:56,439 --> 00:09:59,670
...is to witness the demonstration
of the possibility of movement...

108
00:09:59,742 --> 00:10:02,108
...within the fourth dimension.

109
00:10:08,318 --> 00:10:09,876
Doctor, can I have your help?

110
00:10:09,953 --> 00:10:11,818
Certainly.

111
00:10:35,812 --> 00:10:37,302
It's beautiful.

112
00:10:37,947 --> 00:10:40,108
- Remarkable.
- Very nice, George.

113
00:10:41,618 --> 00:10:42,744
Fascinating.

114
00:10:43,453 --> 00:10:44,613
What is it?

115
00:10:45,021 --> 00:10:47,319
This is only a small experimental model.

116
00:10:50,026 --> 00:10:52,392
To carry a man, a larger edition is needed.

117
00:10:52,462 --> 00:10:54,487
To carry a man? Where?

118
00:10:55,298 --> 00:10:57,391
Into the past or into the future.

119
00:10:58,902 --> 00:11:00,733
This is a time machine.

120
00:11:01,371 --> 00:11:05,831
Now you've had your little joke.
Tell us what this contraption is really for.

121
00:11:05,909 --> 00:11:07,843
I've already told you, Doctor.

122
00:11:08,311 --> 00:11:11,974
The larger model can carry a passenger
on a journey through time.

123
00:11:12,048 --> 00:11:14,676
Not through space, mind you,
but through time.

124
00:11:14,751 --> 00:11:19,211
If you're going to float about in the future,
won't you mess things up for us?

125
00:11:19,389 --> 00:11:22,688
The future's already there.
It's irrevocable and cannot be changed.

126
00:11:25,295 --> 00:11:26,489
I wonder.

127
00:11:28,565 --> 00:11:32,331
That's the most important question
to which I hope to find an answer.

128
00:11:33,236 --> 00:11:35,329
Can man control his destiny?

129
00:11:36,739 --> 00:11:38,866
Can he change the shape
of things to come?

130
00:11:38,942 --> 00:11:41,934
Look, if you've gone out of your head,
I forgive you.

131
00:11:42,111 --> 00:11:44,705
But if you've made us waste all this time...

132
00:11:44,781 --> 00:11:47,272
No, Doctor! You're here as witnesses.

133
00:11:47,850 --> 00:11:49,283
To see, not to listen.

134
00:11:49,352 --> 00:11:50,785
To see? What?

135
00:11:51,521 --> 00:11:53,785
The experiment I am about to perform.

136
00:11:55,191 --> 00:11:56,749
Let me tell you how it works.

137
00:11:57,260 --> 00:12:00,661
Here in this compartment is the saddle
where the time traveler sits.

138
00:12:00,730 --> 00:12:02,527
In front of him are the controls.

139
00:12:03,333 --> 00:12:04,925
Wait, let's do this properly.

140
00:12:05,001 --> 00:12:07,367
You can spare a cigar, I trust, Doctor?

141
00:12:11,107 --> 00:12:13,632
Let us imagine that this cigar...

142
00:12:14,744 --> 00:12:16,439
...is the time traveler.

143
00:12:17,480 --> 00:12:20,779
Now, in front of him is the lever
which controls movement.

144
00:12:21,718 --> 00:12:24,687
Forward pressure sends the machine
into the future...

145
00:12:24,988 --> 00:12:27,616
...backward pressure, into the past.

146
00:12:27,857 --> 00:12:30,792
The harder the pressure,
the faster the machine travels.

147
00:12:32,195 --> 00:12:35,494
Of course, our little experiment
can be performed only once.

148
00:12:36,366 --> 00:12:39,130
If it succeeds, I lose my model forever.

149
00:12:39,936 --> 00:12:41,801
That's why I need witnesses.

150
00:12:43,640 --> 00:12:45,232
Go ahead, George.

151
00:12:46,242 --> 00:12:47,766
Ready, gentlemen?

152
00:12:54,617 --> 00:12:56,608
Lend me your hand, please.

153
00:13:46,302 --> 00:13:48,099
I'll be damned.

154
00:13:48,404 --> 00:13:49,632
It worked.

155
00:13:51,107 --> 00:13:52,631
Where did it go?

156
00:13:53,309 --> 00:13:54,298
Go?

157
00:13:54,444 --> 00:13:57,038
Nowhere, in the usual sense. It's still here.

158
00:13:58,715 --> 00:14:00,683
But it's no longer in the present.

159
00:14:01,951 --> 00:14:05,944
Do you realize it's traveling through time.
To the future, to be exact.

160
00:14:06,122 --> 00:14:08,647
Do you really expect us
to believe such a story?

161
00:14:09,892 --> 00:14:10,881
Certainly.

162
00:14:11,060 --> 00:14:13,392
But you just said it hadn't really moved!

163
00:14:13,463 --> 00:14:14,487
That's correct.

164
00:14:14,564 --> 00:14:16,589
Then why can't we see it?

165
00:14:16,833 --> 00:14:20,132
Because we're in this room
on December 31, 1899...

166
00:14:20,203 --> 00:14:23,900
...but the model we just saw
is perhaps 100 years away by now.

167
00:14:24,040 --> 00:14:27,567
This room, even this whole house,
may not be here in 100 years.

168
00:14:27,643 --> 00:14:31,079
But the time machine occupies
the same space that it did...

169
00:14:31,147 --> 00:14:33,411
...a moment before it went up
on it's journey!

170
00:14:33,483 --> 00:14:37,214
If it's occupying the same space,
why can't I feel it?

171
00:14:37,286 --> 00:14:41,279
Remember that the space you're putting
your hand through is today's space.

172
00:14:41,357 --> 00:14:44,554
You can't put your hand
into the space of tomorrow.

173
00:14:44,927 --> 00:14:47,088
Space is space! It doesn't change!

174
00:14:47,330 --> 00:14:50,857
The same space that's here now
should be here in 100 or even 1,000 years...

175
00:14:50,933 --> 00:14:53,663
No, Philip, time changes space!

176
00:14:54,270 --> 00:14:55,134
No.

177
00:14:56,539 --> 00:14:58,473
This flat ground we're standing on...

178
00:14:58,541 --> 00:15:02,033
...could have been at the bottom of the sea
a million years ago.

179
00:15:02,345 --> 00:15:06,042
A million years from now,
it could be the interior of a huge mountain.

180
00:15:07,250 --> 00:15:09,377
All right, suppose what you say is true.

181
00:15:09,452 --> 00:15:11,977
What do you expect us to do
with such a contraption?

182
00:15:12,822 --> 00:15:13,811
Contraption?

183
00:15:15,758 --> 00:15:18,420
For my part, I intend taking a journey
into the future.

184
00:15:19,996 --> 00:15:22,988
Or perhaps the doctor
would volunteer to go?

185
00:15:24,133 --> 00:15:25,828
Well, look here, George...

186
00:15:25,902 --> 00:15:29,463
...supposing you do go off and get lost
in the 50th century or something...

187
00:15:29,539 --> 00:15:31,598
...how are you going to get back?

188
00:15:31,674 --> 00:15:33,608
That's a risk I'm prepared to take.

189
00:15:34,877 --> 00:15:36,811
Now, look here, George.

190
00:15:37,680 --> 00:15:40,774
I don't know what you take us for,
but we're not fools!

191
00:15:40,850 --> 00:15:42,841
We're practical men, businessmen.

192
00:15:42,919 --> 00:15:45,547
Now, the question I want
to put to you is this:

193
00:15:45,621 --> 00:15:50,024
Even if you had invented a time machine,
or whatever you call it, what of it?

194
00:15:50,092 --> 00:15:52,287
What use would it be?
Who'd want to buy it?

195
00:15:52,361 --> 00:15:54,192
How much would they pay for it?

196
00:15:54,263 --> 00:15:57,426
Yes. Have you thought
of the commercial possibilities?

197
00:15:59,202 --> 00:16:00,430
No, I really haven't.

198
00:16:02,805 --> 00:16:05,035
There's a war on in South Africa.

199
00:16:05,408 --> 00:16:07,672
The Boers are putting up
a pretty stiff fight.

200
00:16:08,077 --> 00:16:10,272
The country needs inventors like you.

201
00:16:11,414 --> 00:16:14,542
I can put you in touch
with the War Office if you wish.

202
00:16:18,588 --> 00:16:20,283
What do you think, David?

203
00:16:22,725 --> 00:16:26,058
Dr. Hillyer has a good point, George.

204
00:16:27,497 --> 00:16:29,397
Now we're becoming more sensible.

205
00:16:29,465 --> 00:16:31,797
I'll see to it the first thing in the new year.

206
00:16:31,868 --> 00:16:34,166
Good Lord! It's time to go, gentlemen.

207
00:16:34,237 --> 00:16:37,468
Yes, I'm sure we all have our plans
for tonight.

208
00:16:39,475 --> 00:16:41,204
Are you all right, George?

209
00:16:42,211 --> 00:16:43,576
Yes, I'm all right.

210
00:16:43,646 --> 00:16:45,307
Coming, Bridewell?

211
00:16:51,787 --> 00:16:53,015
Thank you for coming.

212
00:16:53,089 --> 00:16:55,250
- Good night, George.
- Happy New Year.

213
00:16:55,658 --> 00:16:57,216
Happy New Century, George.

214
00:16:57,293 --> 00:16:58,885
Good night.

215
00:17:17,313 --> 00:17:20,646
Happy New Year!

216
00:18:37,193 --> 00:18:38,660
I thought I'd better stay.

217
00:18:48,971 --> 00:18:52,031
You shouldn't have troubled yourself.
I'm all right.

218
00:18:52,608 --> 00:18:53,905
No, you're not.

219
00:18:54,777 --> 00:18:57,712
You've been behaving oddly
for over a month now.

220
00:18:58,848 --> 00:19:01,908
I'm not leaving here until you tell me
what's on your mind.

221
00:19:01,984 --> 00:19:05,681
I appreciate the gesture.
I just want to be left alone, that's all.

222
00:19:06,756 --> 00:19:09,384
You've changed, George. Enormously.

223
00:19:11,694 --> 00:19:12,922
I'm sorry.

224
00:19:15,865 --> 00:19:18,425
Will you answer me one question,
honestly?

225
00:19:22,838 --> 00:19:23,827
Yes, I'll try.

226
00:19:25,341 --> 00:19:27,969
Why this preoccupation with time?

227
00:19:30,146 --> 00:19:30,874
Why not?

228
00:19:31,981 --> 00:19:33,608
Don't go simple on me, George.

229
00:19:36,986 --> 00:19:40,922
If you want to know the truth, I don't
much care for the time I was born into.

230
00:19:41,590 --> 00:19:44,115
It seems people aren't dying fast enough
these days.

231
00:19:44,593 --> 00:19:48,188
They call upon science to invent new,
more efficient weapons...

232
00:19:48,330 --> 00:19:50,298
...to depopulate the earth.

233
00:19:51,367 --> 00:19:52,994
And I agree with you.

234
00:19:53,235 --> 00:19:57,604
I agree, George, but here we are
and we have to make the best of it.

235
00:19:57,673 --> 00:19:59,698
You may have to. I don't.

236
00:19:59,842 --> 00:20:03,505
All right. Take your journey
on your contraption.

237
00:20:03,612 --> 00:20:05,204
What would you become?

238
00:20:05,981 --> 00:20:07,539
A Greek? A Roman?

239
00:20:08,117 --> 00:20:09,584
One of the Pharaohs?

240
00:20:09,652 --> 00:20:10,846
I prefer the future.

241
00:20:13,055 --> 00:20:15,421
You're not seriously saying you can do it?

242
00:20:17,159 --> 00:20:19,627
You saw the experiment this afternoon,
didn't you?

243
00:20:20,463 --> 00:20:22,693
I saw a toy machine vanish.

244
00:20:24,266 --> 00:20:27,064
I'm sure there are a number of ways
of doing that trick.

245
00:20:28,237 --> 00:20:31,365
Any magician at the hippodrome
could probably do it.

246
00:20:32,208 --> 00:20:33,937
It wasn't a trick.

247
00:20:36,378 --> 00:20:39,870
- Would you like to see the full-scale model?
- No, I would not.

248
00:20:40,049 --> 00:20:43,018
I have no desire to tempt
the laws of Providence.

249
00:20:44,153 --> 00:20:46,121
And I don't think you should.

250
00:20:47,523 --> 00:20:49,514
It's not for man to trifle with.

251
00:20:49,592 --> 00:20:52,060
You're carrying on like Hillyer and Kemp.

252
00:20:52,361 --> 00:20:56,161
There is something to say about
their common-sense attitude to life.

