Do you mean nobody ages
in this land of yours?

486
00:55:32,805 --> 00:55:34,568
What's your name?

487
00:55:35,374 --> 00:55:36,102
Weena.

488
00:55:39,878 --> 00:55:41,641
How do you spell it?

489
00:55:43,882 --> 00:55:44,906
Spell?

490
00:55:45,117 --> 00:55:47,210
Spell. Write. Can't you write?

491
00:55:49,054 --> 00:55:50,021
Look.

492
00:55:57,996 --> 00:55:59,725
What are your people called?

493
00:55:59,798 --> 00:56:00,765
Eloi.

494
00:56:14,213 --> 00:56:15,510
Come. We must go now.

495
00:56:15,581 --> 00:56:17,947
- Why? What's wrong?
- It's getting dark.

496
00:56:46,144 --> 00:56:48,669
I don't mind telling you, I'm quite hungry.

497
00:56:50,382 --> 00:56:52,145
I've come a long, long way.

498
00:56:56,722 --> 00:56:59,213
You know, in my time, a berry that size...

499
00:56:59,525 --> 00:57:02,551
...would've been big news
all over the civilized world.

500
00:57:07,599 --> 00:57:09,089
Excuse me, sir.

501
00:57:11,503 --> 00:57:12,265
Sir?

502
00:57:16,475 --> 00:57:18,943
Perhaps curiosity has died. Perhaps even...

503
00:57:19,144 --> 00:57:21,442
...courtesy has died,
but I've come a long way...

504
00:57:21,513 --> 00:57:23,947
...and I would like to know a few things.

505
00:57:24,516 --> 00:57:25,448
Why?

506
00:57:29,888 --> 00:57:32,413
Because I shall return to my time...

507
00:57:33,225 --> 00:57:36,558
...and my people will ask me questions,
such as:

508
00:57:37,930 --> 00:57:40,398
What kind of government rules your world?

509
00:57:41,166 --> 00:57:43,031
We have no government.

510
00:57:44,836 --> 00:57:49,398
Well, you must have a body of men
who pass and enforce laws.

511
00:57:50,742 --> 00:57:53,006
Laws? There are no laws.

512
00:57:57,282 --> 00:57:59,773
Where do you get your food and clothing?

513
00:58:01,553 --> 00:58:02,850
Doesn't anybody work?

514
00:58:03,956 --> 00:58:04,650
No.

515
00:58:07,326 --> 00:58:09,191
Where does all that come from?

516
00:58:09,628 --> 00:58:11,255
It grows. It always grows.

517
00:58:11,897 --> 00:58:13,524
Yes, I know, but it must be...

518
00:58:14,533 --> 00:58:16,899
...cultivated and planted and nurtured...

519
00:58:20,539 --> 00:58:22,029
Well, unless you...

520
00:58:22,174 --> 00:58:24,734
You mean, you have an economy
so well developed...

521
00:58:24,843 --> 00:58:26,868
...that you can spend all your time...

522
00:58:27,913 --> 00:58:29,505
...studying and experimenting?

523
00:58:29,581 --> 00:58:30,741
Is that right?

524
00:58:31,183 --> 00:58:32,548
You ask many questions.

525
00:58:37,889 --> 00:58:41,017
That is the only way
that man has learned and developed.

526
00:58:41,727 --> 00:58:42,921
I wish to learn.

527
00:58:45,931 --> 00:58:47,159
I want to learn about you.

528
00:58:47,232 --> 00:58:48,927
About your civilization.

529
00:58:57,976 --> 00:58:59,068
Do you have books?

530
00:59:00,412 --> 00:59:01,140
Books?

531
00:59:02,247 --> 00:59:03,475
Yes, we have books.

532
00:59:03,849 --> 00:59:05,180
Wonderful!

533
00:59:05,250 --> 00:59:09,744
I can learn all I want about you from books.
Books will tell me what I want to know.

534
00:59:12,124 --> 00:59:13,716
Could I see the books?

535
00:59:46,725 --> 00:59:49,285
Yes, they do tell me all about you.

536
01:00:04,042 --> 01:00:05,509
What have you done?

537
01:00:06,178 --> 01:00:10,478
Thousands of years of building
and rebuilding, creating and recreating...

538
01:00:10,549 --> 01:00:12,676
...so you can let it crumble to dust!

539
