01:29:31,641 --> 01:29:35,839
<i>Another night was corning,</i>
<i>but this night no Eloi needed to fear.</i>

736
01:29:40,250 --> 01:29:42,980
<i>The underworld</i>
<i>of the Morlocks was gone...</i>

737
01:29:43,453 --> 01:29:46,217
<i>... and so was the life of leisure for the Eloi.</i>

738
01:29:49,659 --> 01:29:51,183
<i>But then what of rne?</i>

739
01:29:51,761 --> 01:29:56,858
<i>I was irnprisoned in a world</i>
<i>in which I just did not belong.</i>

740
01:29:59,536 --> 01:30:00,525
Are you sorry?

741
01:30:03,006 --> 01:30:04,940
Sorry? Sorry for what?

742
01:30:05,475 --> 01:30:06,772
That you have to stay?

743
01:30:10,247 --> 01:30:11,236
Yes.

744
01:30:12,782 --> 01:30:15,876
I'm sorry because I could tell so much
to the people of my time.

745
01:30:16,586 --> 01:30:17,985
I could let them know...

746
01:30:18,722 --> 01:30:22,658
...about the sorrow and the happiness
that the future has in store for them.

747
01:30:22,726 --> 01:30:24,717
Maybe they could learn from it.

748
01:30:26,263 --> 01:30:27,287
Or could they?

749
01:30:30,467 --> 01:30:32,401
You don't want to stay, do you?

750
01:30:32,469 --> 01:30:33,731
It isn't that.

751
01:30:35,071 --> 01:30:37,266
It's just that I don't really fit here...

752
01:30:37,340 --> 01:30:39,604
...any more than you would in my time.

753
01:30:40,277 --> 01:30:42,575
I would love to see your time.

754
01:30:44,047 --> 01:30:45,810
You wouldn't be very happy there.

755
01:30:47,050 --> 01:30:50,110
Do you have someone there?
Someone like me?

756
01:30:51,454 --> 01:30:52,944
No one like you.

757
01:30:56,393 --> 01:30:57,792
I have friends, of course.

758
01:30:57,928 --> 01:30:59,623
Friends who will miss me.

759
01:31:00,263 --> 01:31:02,424
As a matter of fact,
I'm probably late already.

760
01:31:03,400 --> 01:31:04,264
Women?

761
01:31:06,436 --> 01:31:07,130
No.

762
01:31:10,974 --> 01:31:12,373
There is one woman.

763
01:31:14,411 --> 01:31:16,106
She looks after my house for me.

764
01:31:16,179 --> 01:31:19,637
She's 62 years old, all wrinkled,
and nothing like you.

765
01:31:24,521 --> 01:31:26,352
How do they wear their hair?

766
01:31:27,023 --> 01:31:28,854
- Who?
- The women of your time.

767
01:31:32,195 --> 01:31:32,889
Up.

768
01:31:33,563 --> 01:31:34,495
"Up"?

769
01:31:36,600 --> 01:31:37,589
Up how?

770
01:31:38,868 --> 01:31:43,032
I don't know. Kind of... up like that!

771
01:31:45,008 --> 01:31:46,134
Show me!

772
01:32:00,857 --> 01:32:02,518
Would I be pretty?

773
01:32:05,061 --> 01:32:07,291
Yes, you would. Very pretty.

774
01:32:11,968 --> 01:32:14,129
I wish we could go back to my time.

775
01:32:15,071 --> 01:32:18,404
Or even at a time before that,
when the world was young.

776
01:32:18,475 --> 01:32:20,170
We could be so very happy.

777
01:32:20,443 --> 01:32:21,410
Look!

778
01:32:41,865 --> 01:32:43,162
My machine!

779
01:32:45,235 --> 01:32:46,532
Come on, Weena!

780
01:34:06,149 --> 01:34:07,582
<i>I was going the wrong way!</i>

781
01:34:07,650 --> 01:34:10,141
<i>Back! Back! I had to go back!</i>

782
01:36:12,075 --> 01:36:14,566
It's the most ridiculous story
I've ever heard.

783
01:36:14,644 --> 01:36:16,305
Absolutely preposterous!

784
01:36:16,779 --> 01:36:20,613
There's one thing I'll say for old George,
you always could tell a good yarn.

785
01:36:20,683 --> 01:36:23,413
You're a truly great inventor, George.

786
01:36:24,587 --> 01:36:26,782
I think you ought to retire.

787
01:36:28,691 --> 01:36:30,625
Well, truthfully, George...

788
01:36:30,960 --> 01:36:32,928
...where have you been the past week?

789
01:36:32,996 --> 01:36:35,362
You shouldn't ask such questions, Walter.

790
01:36:35,431 --> 01:36:38,867
It is not hard for a man
to lose a little week, now and again.

791
01:36:41,804 --> 01:36:45,740
I can understand your doubt, my friends.
Take it as a lie if you wish.

792
01:36:47,010 --> 01:36:49,774
I scarcely believe it myself,
now that I'm back.

793
01:36:56,719 --> 01:36:59,244
David, there's the flower Weena gave me.

794
01:37:01,858 --> 01:37:03,519
David, a present for you.

795
01:37:03,593 --> 01:37:08,326
You're interested in botany. Try to match
that with any species known today!

796
01:37:13,002 --> 01:37:14,196
I don't think I can.

797
01:37:18,841 --> 01:37:20,468
Time to go, Bridewell.

798
01:37:21,077 --> 01:37:22,806
Yes, it is getting late.

799
01:37:23,046 --> 01:37:24,377
Good night, George.

800
01:37:24,447 --> 01:37:25,914
Good night, George.

801
01:37:31,621 --> 01:37:35,148
You look exhausted, George.
You really should get some rest.

802
01:37:59,949 --> 01:38:02,281
Good night, George.
It's grand having you back.

803
01:38:03,419 --> 01:38:04,443
Goodbye, David.

804
01:38:13,229 --> 01:38:15,629
Thanks for being such a good friend.

805
01:38:15,698 --> 01:38:16,756
Always.

806
01:38:32,348 --> 01:38:34,077
What do you think, Filby?

807
01:38:34,817 --> 01:38:36,409
One thing is certain.

808
01:38:36,486 --> 01:38:39,580
That flower couldn't possibly have bloomed
in the wintertime.

809
01:38:39,655 --> 01:38:42,522
You don't really believe
that story's true, do you?

810
01:38:43,826 --> 01:38:44,918
Good night.

811
01:38:47,063 --> 01:38:47,893
Go on.

812
01:39:37,880 --> 01:39:39,142
He's gone!

813
01:39:41,184 --> 01:39:41,843
Look!

814
01:39:51,661 --> 01:39:55,188
I think I understand. You see the imprint?

815
01:39:56,432 --> 01:39:59,162
This is where the time machine
originally stood.

816
01:40:00,002 --> 01:40:01,594
The Morlocks moved it.

817
01:40:02,772 --> 01:40:04,967
They dragged it across the lawn...

818
01:40:05,608 --> 01:40:07,371
...right into the sphinx.

819
01:40:07,443 --> 01:40:08,569
Right there.

820
01:40:10,346 --> 01:40:13,076
Weena was standing here...

821
01:40:13,816 --> 01:40:15,443
...when he last saw her.

822
01:40:15,518 --> 01:40:16,644
Right here!

823
01:40:16,919 --> 01:40:19,717
The same space in a different time.

824
01:40:22,158 --> 01:40:24,126
He dragged his heavy machine...

825
01:40:24,327 --> 01:40:25,726
...back in here...

826
01:40:26,395 --> 01:40:28,124
...scratching the floor...

827
01:40:29,132 --> 01:40:31,930
...so he could appear
outside the sphinx again...

828
01:40:33,202 --> 01:40:35,568
...and help the Eloi build a new world.

829
01:40:37,640 --> 01:40:39,835
Build a new world for himself.

830
01:40:41,978 --> 01:40:43,878
Right where he left her.

831
01:40:44,013 --> 01:40:44,945
Yes.

832
01:40:55,758 --> 01:40:58,784
It's not like George
to return empty-handed.

833
01:40:59,729 --> 01:41:02,755
To try to rebuild a civilization
without a plan.

834
01:41:04,100 --> 01:41:06,830
He must have taken something with him.

835
01:41:08,804 --> 01:41:10,237
Nothing.

836
01:41:17,346 --> 01:41:18,973
Except three books.

837
01:41:19,415 --> 01:41:21,076
Which three books?

838
01:41:21,884 --> 01:41:23,283
I don't know.

839
01:41:23,819 --> 01:41:25,184
Is it important?

840
01:41:26,923 --> 01:41:28,185
I suppose not.

841
01:41:30,092 --> 01:41:31,252
Only...

842
01:41:32,495 --> 01:41:34,963
...which three books
would you have taken?

843
01:41:41,771 --> 01:41:44,740
Mr. Filby, do you think he'll ever return?

844
01:41:45,408 --> 01:41:47,672
One cannot choose but wonder.

845
01:41:47,743 --> 01:41:48,869
You see...

846
01:41:48,945 --> 01:41:51,470
...he has all the time in the world.

847
